1.18 With each of the following conditions, we recommended to the management to:
Non-conduct of complete physical count of its PPE for CY 2024
Monitor that the Inventory Committee has adequate number of members and representatives from the Accounting and Property Division/Unit for the sole purpose of the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts of the LGU;
Direct the Inventory Committee to plan and strategize the conduct of physical count within the prescribed period and temporarily relieve the members of the latter of all their regular duties in order to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until completed;
c) 	Direct the GSO/Property Unit to record the physical count daily using the ICF per PPE sub-major account group which will be the basis in the preparation of RPCPPE after the physical count;
d) 	Direct the Inventory Committee/GSO/Property Unit to prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station (Annex B of the Circular) and List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) after the physical inventory and submit these lists to the Accounting Unit for recording in the books of accounts of the LGU to establish the existence and proper accountability of the PPE accounts; and
e) 	Ensure that the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided in COA Circular 2020-006 are strictly observed to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.
Presence of bulk acquisitions without specifying quantities
f) 	Direct the Property Unit/GSO and Accounting Unit to exhaust available records and reports in order to trace the specific number of items/quantities on the recorded properties acquired in bulk/by set; and
g) 	Direct the Accounting Unit to ensure that the same meets the capitalization threshold, otherwise, charged the same to expense or Prior Period Adjustment.
Inclusion of doubtful PPE items
h) 	Direct the Municipal Accountant to evaluate PPE items with doubtful costs. Thereafter, if found not to be qualified as part of PPE, drop the accounts through proper journal entry or properly classify to the appropriate SL. Hence, ensure that all property and equipment recorded in the books qualify as PPE pursuant to Item 4.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and COA Circular 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022.
Erroneous and unreliable computation of Accumulated Depreciation
Require the Municipal Accountant to exert more effort in determining the acquisition dates of the PPE sub accounts herein determined to facilitate computation of depreciation for CY 2024 and prior years;
Prepare appropriate adjusting entry taking into consideration the proper treatment of prior period adjustments;
Henceforth, ensure uniform and proper application of depreciation for all the PPE and prepare PPE Lapsing Schedule for monitoring purposes. Also, ensure that the personnel-in-charge for inputting data in the ECPAC system is well-oriented on the application of proper PPE depreciation, and that proper turn-over is conducted in times of manpower movement.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Strictly comply with Section 124, Chapter 7 of the LGU NGAS Manual by requiring the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories at least semiannually and submit the corresponding RPCI to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Immediately require all offices accountable for inventories to submit their detailed updated inventory listings, including all items under their custody as of year-end. They should also provide the current status of said inventories and submit appropriate documentation to support any consumption or distribution that has already occurred;
Designate a qualified General Services Officer (GSO) or assign an accountable central office to oversee inventory management, consolidation, and timely reporting to ensure uniformity and accountability across departments;
Develop and institutionalize a tracking and reconciliation mechanism to ensure timely recording of inventory movements and submission of distribution or utilization reports; and
Conduct periodic orientation or training for inventory custodians and department heads to reinforce compliance with inventory reporting and documentation standards.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
Direct the Municipal Accounting Office to properly present in the comparative financial statements of the ensuing year the completed projects totaling P94.899 million as Prior Period Adjustment account in the comparative financial statements of the next reporting year, in accordance with Annex “B” of COA Circular No. 2015-009 and Paragraph 54 of IPSAS 3. Ensure that the required disclosures detailing the nature and financial impact of the prior period error are included;
Require the full compilation and submission of all supporting documents, including Certificates of Completion and the related Journal Entry Voucher (JEV), to the Commission on Audit (COA) for review and validation of the transaction;
Strengthen internal controls over the recording and disclosure of prior period adjustments within the Municipal Accounting Office; and
Provide regular training to accounting personnel on compliance with applicable accounting standards and COA guidelines to prevent recurrence.

4.7 We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Accounting Office to immediately submit the complete and reliable documentation supporting the P48.134 million recorded assets. At a minimum, the following documents should be provided:
A detailed schedule or computation showing how the adjusted amounts were derived, with clear references to prior year entries and source(s) of funds;
Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) for both the original transactions and the adjusting entries;
Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) for the CIP accounts and related liability accounts ("Due to NGA" and/or "Due to LGU");
Copies of relevant Memoranda of Agreement (MOAs) with source agencies;
Project contracts or Notices of Award for the infrastructure projects involved; and
Project Accomplishment Reports, Statements of Work Accomplished (SWA), and Certificates of Completion or Inspection Reports to validate physical progress.
4.8 Henceforth, ensure that any financial adjustments be made only upon the availability and review of complete documentation.

5.9  We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accounting Office to ensure strict compliance with IPSAS 23, particularly on the recognition of revenue from non-exchange transactions with attached conditions. Furthermore, the accounting deficiencies noted herein should be addressed as prior period misstatements in accordance with IPSAS 3 in the next financial reporting period, through the following measures:
Ensure that revenue is recognized upon fulfillment of the condition attached to the fund transfer, and that the related liability is reduced accordingly, pursuant to Paragraphs 44–45 of IPSAS 23, which require that an inflow of resources be recognized as revenue when the present obligation associated with the condition has been satisfied;
Recognize the corresponding expense or asset, depending on the nature and intended purpose of the fund transfer, to faithfully represent the substance of the transaction in the financial statements;
Rectify prior misstatements, in accordance with IPSAS 3 – Accounting Policies, Changes in Accounting Estimates and Errors, which provides that material prior period errors shall be corrected retrospectively in the financial statements by restating the comparative amounts for the prior period(s) in which the error occurred, or if impracticable, by adjusting the opening balances of assets, liabilities, and net assets/equity for the earliest period practicable;
Institute adequate internal controls and review mechanisms to ensure accurate analysis of stipulations and correct timing of revenue recognition, thereby preventing the recurrence of similar deficiencies in future transactions; and
Require capacity-building programs and continuous training for accounting personnel on IPSAS and other relevant accounting standards to ensure proper understanding and consistent application of accounting principles in line with international standards.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
Require all concerned end-user departments to immediately submit complete and valid supporting documents, such as fuel consumption reports and proof of issuances, for the Fuel, Oil, and Lubricants (FOL) inventory that is no longer physically available but still reflected in the books, to substantiate that said inventory was actually consumed and to allow for appropriate recording of expenses, if warranted;
Strictly enforce compliance with the required submission of fuel consumption reports by all end-user departments to the Accounting Office within a reasonable and defined period after fuel issuance, to ensure timely and accurate recording of expenses and inventory movements;
Designate or establish an accountable unit or personnel, preferably through the creation or formal activation of a General Services Office (GSO), to be primarily responsible for the central monitoring, recording, and reconciliation of Fuel, Oil, and Lubricants (FOL) inventory and usage across all departments;
Implement a clear and documented process flow for fuel issuance, consumption monitoring, and recording, including accountability and timelines for submission of supporting documents;
Develop and maintain a centralized fuel inventory monitoring system, either manual or electronic, that can track real-time inventory balances, fuel issuances, and department-level usage, with regular reconciliation against accounting records;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to ensure retrospective correction of misstatements, if any, by adjusting the overstated Fuel, Oil, and Lubricants Inventory account and recognizing the corresponding expenses through prior period adjustments in compliance with IPSAS 3, and make the necessary disclosures in the notes to the financial statements; and
Institute disciplinary or administrative measures against personnel who consistently fail to comply with fuel documentation and reporting requirements, as part of strengthening internal control and accountability.

8.13 We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
Lead the establishment of a centralized property and supply management system, either through creating a dedicated General Services Office or by designating a specific unit under the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
All transactions related to requisition, issuance, and consumption of inventories must be properly documented using the prescribed forms, such as the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS), Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), and Stock Cards;
Require the submission of the related documents promptly to the Municipal Accounting Office for accurate and timely recording in the books to ensure proper inventory tracking and financial reporting;
Require the different offices responsible of the said inventories to expedite the submission of inventory consumption reports and supporting documents to promote transparency, accountability, and compliance with NGAS standards;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to scrutinize the submitted documents as to completeness, accuracy, and validity, and to affect the necessary adjustments in the books if found proper and supported; and
Require the LGU offices concerned to prioritize responding on pending audit inquiries and ensure the timely submission of all required supporting documents to address outstanding audit observations and prevent recurrence of inventory control deficiencies.

9.6  We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Revisit and thoroughly review the accounting treatment of the receipt and utilization of unspent Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Funds (DRRMF) in accordance with the guidelines set forth under COA Circular No. 2012-002 and COA Circular No. 2015-009, particularly on the proper use of the accounts;
Make the necessary adjusting entries in CY 2025 to correct the affected balances and ensure the proper classification of the unspent DRRMF, and recognize the prior period error in accordance with IPSAS 3 by disclosing the nature of the error, the amount of the correction, and its impact on the comparative financial statements in the Notes to the CY 2025 Financial Statements;
Submit the necessary supporting documents for the P401,000.00 reported debits to facilitate verification and establish the validity of the transactions; and
Institute internal control measures, including periodic reviews and proper documentation of fund transfers and disbursements, to prevent recurrence of similar misstatements in future financial reports.

We recommended to the management to:
Evaluate the semi-expendable items still recorded under the Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) and reclassify to the appropriate expense or inventory accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
Establish controls and accountability for semi-expendable properties such as maintenance of Semi-Expendable Property Card (SPC), Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card (SPLC), Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued (RegSPI) and other prescribed forms under COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022 as maybe applicable such as Inventory Transfer Report (ITR), Receipt of Returned Semi-Expendable Property (RRSP), and Report of Semi-Expendable Property Issued (RSPI);
Through the coordination of the Inventory Committee, plan and conduct the physical count of the LGU’s semi-expendable properties in a regular basis and accomplish the Report on Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property (RPCSP). Also, conduct periodic inventory reviews to identify and correct misclassifications in the LGU’s records and to ensure that only qualified items are capitalized as PPE; and
Assign accountable personnel/office for inventory management to ensure ongoing compliance, accurate tracking, and proper valuation of semi-expendable properties in subsequent reporting period.

14.7 We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to require strict documentation of the consumption of Fuel, Oil and Lubricants according to COA Circular No. 75-6 dated November 7, 1975 and establish sound internal controls on its POL consumptions through the following:
Driver's Trip Tickets must be properly accomplished with complete details with name/s of authorized passenger/s, time of departure and arrivals, fuel issued, purchased and consumed or Gear/Lubricant/Grease oil issued;
Monthly report of official travels must be duly prepared by the driver for each motor vehicle approved by the Administrative Officer concerned;
Establish efficient and effective controls on the monitoring of the fuel consumption such as assignment of knowledgeable personnel-in-charge and creation of functioning GSO. Also, ensure proper and timely reconciliations of fuel balances with the monthly report of official travels prepared by the drivers for each motor vehicle;
Ensure that Fuel Consumption Reports bear proper signatures of accountable officials and employees and contain necessary details for easy monitoring such as page numbers, subtotals and the like;
Adjustments from the price originally stated in the PO (price escalation/de-escalation) must be supported by proper invoices and billing statements from suppliers showing the said price escalation/de-escalation properly showing prices on the actual date of withdrawal;
Include only in the consumption reports the supporting documents relative to its PR and PO; and
Ensure that fuel consumption documents are valid and reliable, such that transactions with the supplier evidenced by gas slips and trip tickets and other supporting documents must be done (and dated) after conducting the proper procurement process.
14.8 Also, submit justification of the LGU’s deviation from the above enumerated documentary requirements and controls.
14.9 Moreover, we recommended the management to immediately submit the lacking fuel consumption report, the required supporting documents and monthly report of official travel and other fuel consumption report as enumerated on the herein observation, subject for evaluation.

